														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1267077">
									

<p>TO THE PURPLEST</p>
<p>Actually, the (incredibly) purple prose works quite well for me as a portrayal of a seriously disturbed character (schizophrenic? I didn't look it up). I like the touches of him suffering from an inability to say <em>anything</em> when he tries to actually speak; presumably his very purple thought process is a step away from this.</p>
<p>I also like it in context of the Little Misters series; several of the theoretically insane things this character thinks make more sense when you've read the perspectives of the others. And there's the fridge logic: Mr. Purple only <em>thinks</em> in purple prose. He can barely <em>talk</em> at all. Is he a Mister that got fucked up in whatever creation or alteration process Wondertainment uses? Or was it intentional to force him to only communicate through writing? (Though the fact that he writes &quot;Liar&quot; but doesn't know why may mean he can't even communicate that way outside his own head.)</p>
<p>(oh the irony of overanalyzing something that's deliberately overwritten)</p>
<p>So, upvoted.</p>

							</div>

								
					
